Letter from the Mayor


Dear Washingtonians,

By now, many of you have read or heard this week's NPR story on Ballou
High School. I want you to hear directly from me that we take this
seriously. It is important that all of our students get the education
they need to be college and career ready.

Today, after an initial assessment of the allegations made in the news
report, I signed a Mayor's Order directing the Office of the State
Superintendent of Education (OSSE), our state education department and
regulator, to review district-wide policies and investigate specific
allegations at the school level. OSSE is engaging the support of an
outside firm to assist them with this review and investigation and will
deliver its findings to me within 45 days.=20

Parents, students, or educators who have questions or concerns should
call the Office of the Deputy Mayor for Education at (202) 727-3636. We
want to hear from you. =20

Let me be very clear: we are working hard to remove barriers to student
attendance. Several years ago, we ensured that every public school
student can ride free on Metrobus and Metrorail. And just this year, we
launched the Every Day Counts! campaign to gain community support for
boosting student attendance and achievement.

Now, we must ensure that our attendance policies are clear, transparent,
and consistently administered for every child, at every school, and
every day. I can ensure you that we will find out if mistakes were made
and we will fix them.=20

Sincerely,=20

 Muriel
